The electrochemical carbon dioxide reduction reaction(ECRR)can simultaneously realize the storage of intermittent renewable electricity and net decrease of greenhouse gas [1].On one hand,a large number of materials have been developed as efficient catalysts for ECRR with remarkable selectivity or faradaic efficiency [2].On the other hand,increasing current densities to satisfy the demand of industrial operation(e.g.,>200 mA cm~(-2))requires enough CO_2 reactant to be supplied to the catalyst layer,otherwise it will lead to severe hydrogen evolution reaction and low energy efficiency [3].Unfortunately,traditional H-type electrochemical reactors can hardly fulfill this request,due to the very limited solubility and diffusion coefficient of CO_2 in aqueous solution.Consequently,more and more researchers have attempted to deposit proper ECRR catalysts onto specific gas-diffusion layers(GDLs)to assemble so-called gas-diffusion electrodes(GDEs)[4].With the assistance of this GDE device,significantly high concentration of CO_2 reactant can still be maintained around the catalyst layer even at high reaction rates,producing >200 mA cm~(-2)current densities in a few recent reports [3-5].In most of the cases,the catalyst layers were directly loaded onto commercially purchased GDLs such as Sigracet 39BC via electrodeposition or polymer binders(e.g.,Nafion)[4].The invariant mechanical and chemical properties of these GDLs might restrict the CO_2 reduction applications in the future.Furthermore,the weak binding between catalyst layers and GDLs could also have adverse effect on the stable long-term operation,especially at >200 mA cm~(-2)current densities.Increase usage of polymer binders may reduce the catalyst powder falling off,but it will significantly restrain the mass transfer and electron transport.Therefore,the design and creation of new GDE device for ECRR is still an important and challenging task.
